'''Claude Moët''' (1683–1760) was a [[France|French]] [[Winemaker|vintner]] and [[wine]] merchant who founded the [[Champagne]] house that later became [[Moët & Chandon|Moët et Chandon]]. Moët was the first winemaker in [[Champagne (wine region)|Champagne]] to exclusively produce [[sparkling wine]]. An expert salesman, Moët advocated the importance of personal contact with customers. During the 1730s, he networked extensively within the royal circles of [[Palace of Versailles|Versailles]] and soon became one of few merchants accredited to serve the royal court. One of his most loyal customers was the [[Madame de Pompadour]].<ref name="Kladstrup pg 47-48">D. & P. Kladstrup ''Champagne'' pg 47-48 Harper Collins Publisher {{ISBN|0-06-073792-1}}</ref> Following his death the champagne house went to the control of his grandson [[Jean-Rémy Moët]]. And soon after he died from a heart attack.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
==Family history== The Moët family can trace its origins to a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] soldier named LeClerc who fought alongside [[Joan of Arc]] in fending off [[England|English]] attempts at preventing the crowning of [[Charles VII of France|Charles VII]]. As a reward for his service, the King changed his name to Moët.<ref name="Kladstrup pg 48">D. & P. Kladstrup ''Champagne'' pg 48 Harper Collins Publisher {{ISBN|0-06-073792-1}}</ref>
==See also== *[[List of wine personalities]]
