[[Image:Portrait of Princess Maria Josefa Hermenegilde von Esterhazy (1793) Le Brun.jpg|thumbnail|1793 portrait by [[Élisabeth Vigée Le Brun]] ([[Liechtenstein Museum]])]] '''Maria Josepha Hermengilde Esterházy de Galantha''' (born '''von Liechtenstein''', 13 April, 1768 — 8 August, 1845) was the daughter of [[Franz Josef I of Liechtenstein]]. On 15 September 1783 she married Prince [[Nikolaus II, Prince Esterházy|Nikolaus II Esterházy de Galantha]], who in 1794 became the Prince of [[Esterházy]]. In 1785 she bore a son, [[Paul III Anton, Prince Esterházy|Paul Anton]] and in 1788 a daughter, Leopoldine.
==Patroness== Like her husband Maria was a patron of artists, and especially of [[Joseph Haydn]], who from 1796 to 1802 was commissioned to write a yearly [[Mass (music)|Mass]] to be performed on her [[nameday]] (8 September, the [[Nativity of Mary|Nativity of the BVM]]<ref>[[List of Masses by Joseph Haydn]] gives the more plausible Sept. 12, [[The Most Holy Name of the Blessed Virgin Mary]] </ref>). Thus originated the ''[[Heiligmesse]]'' (1796), ''[[Paukenmesse]]'' (1797), ''[[Missa in Angustiis|Nelsonmesse]]'' (1798), ''[[Theresienmesse]]'' (1799), ''[[Schöpfungsmesse]]'' (1801) and ''[[Harmoniemesse]]'' (1802). For her 1807 nameday [[Ludwig van Beethoven]] composed his ''[[Mass in C major (Beethoven)|''Mass in C major, op. 86'']].
